  <example xml:id="ex-not-skew">
<statement>
<p>
Show that the lines with the following vector forms are not skew:
<md>
<mrow>
\ell_1: \amp  \qquad \vect{x} = s[1, 1, 1], \qquad s\in \R  \\
\ell_2: \amp  \qquad \vect{x} = t[1, 2, 3], \qquad t\in \R
</mrow>
</md>.
Substituting <m>s = 0</m> into the vector form for <m>\ell_1</m> gives <m>\vect{x} = [0, 0, 0]</m>. 
Substituting <m>t = 0</m> into the vector form for <m>\ell_2</m> gives <m>\vect{x} = [0, 0, 0]</m>. 
Therefore the lines intersect at <m>(0, 0, 0)</m>, so they are not skew.
</p>
</statement>
</example>

<example xml:id="ex-determining-skew">
<statement>
<p>
Determine whether the lines with the following vector forms are skew
<md>
<mrow>
\ell_1: \amp  \qquad \vect{x} = [1, 0, -2] + s[1, 1, 1], \qquad s\in \R   \\
\ell_2: \amp  \qquad \vect{x} = [1, 2, 3] + t[1, -1, -2], \qquad t\in \R
</mrow>
</md>.
The lines are not parallel since the direction vectors <m>\vect{d}_1 = [1, 1, 1]</m> and 
<m>\vect{d}_2 = [1, -1, 2]</m> are not parallel. To determine whether the lines intersect, we 
try to equate their parametric equations:
<me>
\begin{cases}
  1+s    = 1+ t \\
  s      = 2-t  \\
  -2+s   = 3-2t 
\end{cases}
</me>
which rearranges to give
<me>
\begin{cases}
  s-t  = 0 \\
  s+t  = 2 \\
  s+2t = 5
\end{cases}
</me>.
Solving the first two equations gives <m>s = t=1</m>, but substituting this into the third equation 
gives <m>s + 2t = 3 \ne 5</m>. Therefore this system of equations has no solutions, so the lines do 
not intersect. Therefore <m>\ell_1</m> and <m>\ell_2</m> are skew.
</p>
</statement>
</example>

</section>


